      }
    },
    {
      "name": "Bash",
      "args": {
        "command": "cat stm32-project.jsonc 2>/dev/null || ls",
        "description": "Check project descriptor for target board"
      }
    },
    {
      "name": "Bash",
      "args": {
        "command": "STM32_PROGRAMMER_DEFAULT_SN=066DFF485754727567021514 stm32 debug read-peripheral SPI SPI1",
        "description": "Read SPI1 registers on the L476 via its probe"
      }
    },
    {
      "name": "Bash",
      "args": {
        "command": "STM32_PROGRAMMER_DEFAULT_SN=066DFF485754727567021514 stm32 debug read-peripheral SPI1",
        "description": "Read SPI1 registers on the L476"
      }
    },
    {
      "name": "Bash",
      "args": {
        "command": "STM32_PROGRAMMER_DEFAULT_SN=066DFF485754727567021514 stm32 debug read-peripheral RCC | python3 -c \"import json,sys; d=json.load(sys.stdin); r=d['registers']['APB2ENR']; print('APB2ENR raw =', hex(r['raw_value'])); [print(f\\\"  {n}: {f['raw_value']}\\\") for n,f in r['fields'].items()]\"",
        "description": "Check RCC APB2ENR for SPI1 clock enable"
      }
    }
  ],
  "final_text": "The project targets the NUCLEO-L476RG, so I'll pin its probe:\n**No \u2014 SPI1 is not enabled, and in fact it's never been touched.**\n\nTwo findings from the live target (NUCLEO-L476RG, attached without reset, halted in place):\n\n1. **`SPI1.CR1` = 0x0000 \u2192 SPE (bit 6) = 0.** The peripheral-enable bit is clear \u2014 but that read is actually moot, because:\n\n2. **`RCC.APB2ENR.SPI1EN` = 0** \u2014 SPI1's bus clock is gated off entirely. With the clock disabled, the peripheral's registers read as zero regardless of content. The tell was `CRCPR` reading 0 when its hardware reset value is `0x0007`.\n\nSo the failure is upstream of `SPE`: the firmware never enabled the SPI1 clock (`__HAL_RCC_SPI1_CLK_ENABLE()` / setting `RCC->APB2ENR |= RCC_APB2ENR_SPI1EN`), so any `SPI1->CR1 |= SPI_CR1_SPE` write \u2014 if one exists \u2014 would have been silently dropped. Check that the clock-enable call runs (it normally lives in `HAL_SPI_MspInit()`) before chasing the SPE write itself.\n\n(Note: this firmware is the BLINKY descriptor's default project, which doesn't configure SPI at all \u2014 if you meant to inspect a different SPI firmware, it may not be what's currently flashed/running on the L476.)"
}